.TH "gdu" "1" "2026-07-20" "" ""
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
gdu - Pretty fast disk usage analyzer written in Go
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]gdu [flags] [directory_to_scan]\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]gdu snapshots [list] [file.parquet]\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]gdu snapshots compact [--dry-run]\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Pretty fast disk usage analyzer written in Go.
.PP
Gdu is intended primarily for SSD disks where it can fully utilize
parallel processing.
However HDDs work as well, but the performance gain is not so huge.
.PP
This fork records history: every completed interactive scan is archived
as a Parquet snapshot (see \f[B]--save-snapshots\f[R]).
In the TUI, \f[B]S\f[R] compares the view against a snapshot (growth
diff), \f[B][\f[R] and \f[B]]\f[R] step the view itself through this
folder\[cq]s snapshots, and \f[B]O\f[R] opens any archived snapshot;
snapshot views are read-only, with a guided way back to the live disk.
While a scan is still running, \f[B]Tab\f[R] previews the partial tree
found so far (\f[B][\f[R]/\f[B]]\f[R] still step into past snapshots);
the two are complementary \[em] \f[B]Tab\f[R] browses the present being
built, \f[B][\f[R]/\f[B]]\f[R] the past already recorded.
.PP
Bare \f[B]gdu\f[R], \f[B]gdu\f[R] <path>, and interactive \f[B]gdu
-d\f[R] open an interactive \f[B]launcher\f[R] \[em] the familiar device
table with the folder you\[cq]re in pinned first, its disk pinned
directly below it, and a Scan-another-folder opener pinned last; each
row shows its newest snapshot once history exists.
\f[B]Enter\f[R] scans the selected row, \f[B]s\f[R] opens its latest
snapshot without scanning, \f[B]S\f[R] picks a specific one, \f[B]n\f[R]
sorts the other disks.
When gdu is not running as root, \f[B]R\f[R] restarts it under
\f[B]sudo\f[R] (you are prompted for your password, and the elevated gdu
reopens the launcher); scanning the whole root volume (\f[B]/\f[R])
always confirms this first.
An explicit path pre-selects the folder row; a bare launch the
folder\[cq]s disk \[em] and choosing that disk opens at the folder
you\[cq]re in, not the disk root (the whole disk is still scanned).
On macOS the synthetic \f[B]/System/Volumes/\f[R] volumes are hidden
from the launcher (not from the classic \f[B]gdu -d\f[R] table).
It is skipped by \f[B]--snapshot\f[R], \f[B]-f\f[R],
\f[B]--read-from-storage\f[R], \f[B]--db\f[R], and non-interactive mode;
\f[B]--launcher=false\f[R] (config \f[B]launcher: false\f[R]) restores
upstream scan-immediately behavior.
.SH COMMANDS
.PP
\f[B]gdu snapshots [list] [file.parquet]\f[R] List every snapshot in the
snapshot archive (--snapshots-dir), newest first, or the snapshots held
in one Parquet snapshot file (\[dq]-\[dq] reads from standard input).
Command alias: \f[B]snaps\f[R]; verb alias: \f[B]ls\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]gdu snapshots compact [--dry-run]\f[R] Merge each closed
month\[cq]s snapshots in the archive into one monthly Parquet file per
scan root (lossless; sources are deleted only after the result is
verified).
With \f[B]--dry-run\f[R], print what would be compacted without writing
or deleting anything.
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\f[B]-h\f[R], \f[B]--help\f[R][=false] help for gdu
.PP
\f[B]-i\f[R], \f[B]--ignore-dirs\f[R]=[/proc,/dev,/sys,/run] Paths to
ignore (separated by comma).
Supports both absolute and relative paths.
.PP
\f[B]-I\f[R], \f[B]--ignore-dirs-pattern\f[R] Path patterns to ignore
(separated by comma).
Supports both absolute and relative path patterns.
.PP
\f[B]-X\f[R], \f[B]--ignore-from\f[R] Read path patterns to ignore from
file.
Supports both absolute and relative path patterns.
.PP
\f[B]-T\f[R], \f[B]--type\f[R] File types to include (e.g., \[en]type
yaml,json)
.PP
\f[B]-E\f[R], \f[B]--exclude-type\f[R] File types to exclude (e.g.,
\[en]exclude-type yaml,json)
.PP
\f[B]--max-age\f[R] Include files with mtime no older than DURATION
(e.g., 7d, 2h30m, 1y2mo)
.PP
\f[B]--min-age\f[R] Include files with mtime at least DURATION old
(e.g., 30d, 1w)
.PP
\f[B]--since\f[R] Include files with mtime >= WHEN.
WHEN accepts RFC3339 timestamp (e.g., 2025-08-11T01:00:00-07:00) or date
only YYYY-MM-DD (calendar-day compare; includes the whole day)
.PP
\f[B]--until\f[R] Include files with mtime <= WHEN.
WHEN accepts RFC3339 timestamp or date only YYYY-MM-DD
.PP
\f[B]-l\f[R], \f[B]--log-file\f[R]=\[dq]/dev/null\[dq] Path to a logfile
.PP
\f[B]-m\f[R], \f[B]--max-cores\f[R] Set max cores that Gdu will use.
.PP
\f[B]-c\f[R], \f[B]--no-color\f[R][=false] Do not use colorized output
.PP
\f[B]-x\f[R], \f[B]--no-cross\f[R][=false] Do not cross filesystem
boundaries
.PP
\f[B]-H\f[R], \f[B]--no-hidden\f[R][=false] Ignore hidden directories
(beginning with dot)
.PP
\f[B]-L\f[R], \f[B]--follow-symlinks\f[R][=false] Follow symlinks for
files, i.e.\ show the size of the file to which symlink points to
(symlinks to directories are not followed)
.PP
\f[B]-n\f[R], \f[B]--non-interactive\f[R][=false] Do not run in
interactive mode
.PP
\f[B]--interactive\f[R][=false] Force interactive mode even when output
is not a TTY
.PP
\f[B]-p\f[R], \f[B]--no-progress\f[R][=false] Do not show progress in
non-interactive mode
.PP
\f[B]-u\f[R], \f[B]--no-unicode\f[R][=false] Do not use Unicode symbols
(for size bar)
.PP
\f[B]-s\f[R], \f[B]--summarize\f[R][=false] Show only a total in
non-interactive mode
.PP
\f[B]--export-threshold\f[R][=\[lq]0\[rq]] Bucket objects smaller than
this size into a `' rollup on export.
Binary units: 10M, 500K, 2G, or plain bytes.
0 = keep everything.
.PP
\f[B]-t\f[R], \f[B]--top\f[R][=0] Show only top X largest files in
non-interactive mode
.PP
\f[B]-d\f[R], \f[B]--show-disks\f[R][=false] Show all mounted disks
(interactively, opens the launcher with its disks section focused)
.PP
\f[B]--launcher\f[R][=true] Open the interactive launcher (folder, its
disk, your other disks, snapshots) instead of scanning immediately.
\f[B]--launcher=false\f[R] (or \f[B]launcher: false\f[R] in config)
restores upstream scan-immediately behavior.
Ignored in non-interactive mode.
.PP
\f[B]-a\f[R], \f[B]--show-apparent-size\f[R][=false] Show apparent size
.PP
\f[B]-C\f[R], \f[B]--show-item-count\f[R][=false] Show number of items
in directory
.PP
\f[B]-k\f[R], \f[B]--show-in-kib\f[R][=false] Show sizes in KiB (or kB
with \[en]si) in non-interactive mode
.PP
\f[B]-M\f[R], \f[B]--show-mtime\f[R][=false] Show latest mtime of items
in directory
.PP
\f[B]--archive-browsing\f[R][=false] Enable browsing of zip/jar/tar
archives (tar, tar.gz, tar.bz2, tar.xz)
.PP
\f[B]--depth\f[R][=0] Show directory structure up to specified depth in
non-interactive mode (0 means the flag is ignored)
.PP
\f[B]--collapse-path\f[R][=false] Collapse single-child directory chains
.PP
\f[B]--mouse\f[R][=false] Use mouse
.PP
\f[B]--si\f[R][=false] Show sizes with decimal SI prefixes (kB, MB, GB)
instead of binary prefixes (KiB, MiB, GiB)
.PP
\f[B]--no-prefix\f[R][=false] Show sizes as raw numbers without any
prefixes (SI or binary) in non-interactive mode
.PP
\f[B]--no-spawn-shell\f[R][=false] Do not allow spawning shell
.PP
\f[B]--no-confirm-quit\f[R][=false] Do not ask for confirmation before
quitting after a long scan
.PP
\f[B]--no-delete\f[R][=false] Do not allow deletions
.PP
\f[B]--no-view-file\f[R][=false] Do not allow viewing file contents
.PP
\f[B]-f\f[R], \f[B]--input-file\f[R] Import analysis from JSON or
Parquet file (format auto-detected).
If the file is \[dq]-\[dq], read from standard input.
.PP
\f[B]-o\f[R], \f[B]--output-file\f[R] Export all info into file as JSON.
If the file is \[dq]-\[dq], write to standard output.
.PP
\f[B]--output-format\f[R] Export format: json (default) or parquet.
Inferred from the -o file extension when unset.
.PP
\f[B]--save-snapshots\f[R][=\[lq]auto\[rq]] When to save each completed
scan of a chosen root as a Parquet snapshot in the snapshots directory
(auto|always|never, default auto): auto saves interactive scans only,
always saves in every mode (forcing the full-tree analyzer
non-interactively), never disables saving.
Refreshes (r) and go-live spot-rescans never save; quitting mid-scan
asks and discards.
Snapshot rollup threshold defaults to 10M.
.PP
\f[B]--snapshots-dir\f[R] Directory for saved snapshots (default
$XDG_DATA_HOME/gdu/snapshots, i.e.\ \[ti]/.local/share/gdu/snapshots).
.PP
\f[B]--snapshot\f[R] Which snapshot to load: latest, earliest, or a
local timestamp/prefix like 2026-06-19 or 2026-06-19T15:30:05.
With -f, selects within that file; without -f, resolves against the
archive for snapshots of the scanned path and loads the match.
.PP
\f[B]--snapshot-root\f[R] Restrict \[en]snapshot selection to this exact
scan root (rarely needed; the positional path is the primary scope
without -f).
.PP
\f[B]--baseline\f[R] Interactive: open in growth-diff mode against this
baseline \[em] a Parquet snapshot file, or a selector (latest, earliest,
or a timestamp prefix) resolved against the archive\[cq]s snapshots
covering the scanned path on the same volume.
Pick another baseline in the TUI with S.
.PP
\f[B]--baseline-root\f[R] Restrict a \[en]baseline selector to snapshots
of this exact scan root (also reaches across volumes).
.PP
\f[B]--no-auto-compact\f[R][=false] Do not compact the archive\[cq]s
closed months after a snapshot is saved.
.PP
\f[B]--owner\f[R] Make written output (snapshots, -o exports) owned by
this user: resolves their home for the default snapshots-dir and chowns
output to them.
For scheduled root scans.
.PP
\f[B]--config-file\f[R] Read config from file (default is
\[ti]/.config/gdu/gdu.yaml, or \[ti]/.gdu.yaml if that exists)
.PP
\f[B]--write-config\f[R][=false] Write current configuration to file
(the config that would be read: an existing user config, else
\[ti]/.config/gdu/gdu.yaml, creating the directory)
.PP
\f[B]--enable-profiling\f[R][=false] Enable collection of profiling data
and provide it on http://localhost:6060/debug/pprof/
.PP
\f[B]-D\f[R], \f[B]--db\f[R] Store analysis in database (\f[I].sqlite
for SQLite, \f[R].badger for BadgerDB)
.PP
\f[B]-r\f[R], \f[B]--read-from-storage\f[R][=false] Use existing
database instead of re-scanning
.PP
\f[B]-v\f[R], \f[B]--version\f[R][=false] Print version
.SH HISTORY KEYS
.PP
In the TUI, once the archive holds snapshots covering the current
folder:
.TP
\f[B][\f[R] / \f[B]]\f[R]
Step the view to an older / newer snapshot of the current folder (same
folder, same cursor).
At the newest, \f[B]]\f[R] returns to the live view \[em] instantly when
the live tree is still in memory, otherwise via an explicit rescan
offer.
.TP
\f[B]S\f[R]
Pick a baseline snapshot covering this folder on its volume (the picker
lists each snapshot\[cq]s scan root, size of this folder, and change
since; a host column shows only for snapshots from another machine);
every row then carries a signed growth delta (\f[B]>\f[R] / \f[B]<\f[R]
sort by growth).
.TP
\f[B]O\f[R]
Open any archived snapshot \[em] all roots and dates \[em] as the view.
.TP
\f[B]Esc\f[R]
Layered and always instant: close an overlay, else clear the baseline,
else return to where the session started.
Esc never scans.
.PP
Snapshot views (including \f[B]-f\f[R] imports) are read-only:
\f[B]d\f[R], \f[B]e\f[R] and \f[B]r\f[R] offer \f[I]go live here\f[R]
\[em] an instant switch when a live tree covering the folder is in
memory, else a confirmed scan of just that folder.
Refreshes and those spot-rescans never save a snapshot; only completed
scans of a deliberately chosen root are recorded.
.SH FILE FLAGS
.PP
Files and directories may be prefixed by a one-character flag with
following meaning:
.TP
\f[B]!\f[R]
An error occurred while reading this directory.
.TP
\f[B].\f[R]
An error occurred while reading a subdirectory, size may be not correct.
.TP
\f[B]\[at]\f[R]
File is symlink or socket.
.TP
\f[B]H\f[R]
Same file was already counted (hard link).
.TP
\f[B]e\f[R]
Directory is empty.
